        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p>
                <placeName>Tioga Centre</placeName>
                <date>Sept 16<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1861</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. I Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I presume you did not<lb/> receive a message which I sent you this
                one<lb/> of my friends in <date>July</date>, informing you of my present address, as
                both <date>July</date> &amp; <date>August</date>, No.<lb/> of the Occident were
                directed to <placeName>Binghamton</placeName>â€”<lb/> both of which No., have been
                forwarded to me.<lb/> You will please direct here after until you<lb/> hear to the
                contrary. To the care of <persName>Mr.<lb/> Gilbert Strang</persName>,
                    <placeName>Tioga Centre, Tioga<lb/> County N Y</placeName>. I have been here
                since<lb/> the <date>16th of July</date>, I am again boarding<lb/> in a Christian
                family, not having heard of<lb/> a Jewish one, to whom I could apply.<lb/> The
                family is very small, &amp; I am the only<lb/> Boarder, I should prefer were there
                two or three<lb/> other pleasant ones, especially as the lady of<lb/> the house is
                much occupied in her domestic<lb/> duties, her Husband &amp; Son, a lad, compose
                her<lb/> family. The place is very small, &amp; quiet, it is 6</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>miles from <placeName>Oswego</placeName>.</p>
            <p>I thank you much for supplying my missing<lb/> No of the Occident, some time previous
                to<lb/> my leaving <placeName>Binghamton</placeName> together with your<lb/>
                accompanying kind letter. Soon after the rect.<lb/> of which, in a letter addressed
                to my cousin<lb/>
                <persName>Mrs. D. C. Levy</persName>, I asked her to say to you I had<lb/> recd.
                them &amp; thanked you kindly for the same.<lb/> I hope she remembered to give you
                my message.<lb/> I suppose herself &amp; family have returned to the<lb/> City, if
                so, when next you see them, please extend<lb/> my love to them. I regret that you
                thought<lb/> it hopeless for you to make <add>any</add> effort to become<lb/> the
                medium of bring<add>ing</add> about <sic>pease</sic> to this
                    dis-<lb/><sic>tructed</sic> Country. I noticed in some recent papers<lb/> that
                there are some who are not only opposed to the<lb/> peace-meetings, that have been
                held in this state<lb/> but denounce them, &amp; since which the press has<lb/> been
                in some instances silenced &amp; are making every<lb/> effort to urge on this
                horrible war. May God in His<lb/> Mercy &amp; wisdom see fit to arrest this cruel
                war<lb/> at once, &amp; grant us peace &amp; prosperity tho we</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>be undeserving some of us.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With the hope of a brighter future</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Truly your friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">R. A. L.</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
